On 6/29/2015 at 18:11 Padre Dam received a call from the owner of the property about sewage leaking from the manhole located in his back yard. The after-hours person responded to the location and found the manhole surcharged and a small amount of water had leaked from between the 1st and 2nd grade ring below the lid. The depth of the manhole is about 18 feet it was determined that the lateral had failed in the past and had been reinstalled into the manhole instead of repairing the initial lateral. Now with no way to drain due to the new liner it finally reached its capacity and leaked through the exposed grade ring.

We then dye tested the lateral and the main again as well. The last main dye test revealed a problem in the line. The line is on an easement and the terrain is treacherous. We took into account that the water was no where near a storm drain and that the leak was very minimal. We also took precaution by letting the residents on the line know about the problem and had them limit their use. There were only 2 laterals on the line that contributed to the problem. We contacted a few pipe lining companies to line the pipe which we considered our solution of the problem. When it was revealed the line couldn't be lined or pipe bursted we pipe patched every joint on the line until the problem was solved.

During the process of installing a new section of Forcemain. Operations was asked to switched back to a 48 inch RCP that was recently placed out of service. Previously while the 48 inch RCP was going out of service a manway cover was removed to assist in the process. Afterwards the cover  of the manway was placed back on, but only with every other bolt in place.  As the system line pressures came up in the morning of the 8th leaking around the cover began due to the empty bolt holes. The Operations group then reduced the flow in order to reduce the system line pressure to stop the dripping.  The Maintenance department was then notified to install the missing bolts. Once this was accomplished the system was placed back to full operations and the drips from around the man way cover where were no longer present.

Due to grease clogging the ARV assembly. Sewage was slowing leaking from the ARV. On July 8th a standby 48 inch RCP Forcemain was placed in-service. On July 20th a scheduled PM to swap the auto air relief with a clean one was performed. Upon arriving at the air relief site the operator found that sewage had leaked from the discharge of the air relief and filled a 5 gallon overflow bucket. There was also evidence that sewage had leaked from the bucket. The evidence of leaking from the bucket was due to the fact that the immediate soil around the bucket was wet. There was no standing water around the bucket, so the estimate of amount spilled. The mitigation from the leak was to remove the wet soil with a shovel. The soil was then dumped into one 5 gallon bucket. Because there is no means to determine a exact start time of the leak the date of the Forcemain going into service was used.

SPILL CAUSE EXPLAIN: At approximately 3:45 pm a representative from Golden State Water contacted Richard Hecker, Claremont Landscape Supervisor, indicating the contractor had hit a sewer line. Mr. Hecker notified Mike Mc Cabe, Maintenance Supervisor, who is responsible for the maintenance of the City's sewer system. Both Supervisors arrived on scene within 5 minutes of the call. To which they found GSW crews pumping sewage overflow directly into the storm drain. City staff directed to stop pumping into the storm drain and divert into the next manhole. The contractor did not have the proper equipment and had to call for assistance. In less than 30 minutes the contractor received the equipment necessary to divert to the next manhole. The debris from the broken pipe also caused a backup in the line, enabling the line to flow properly. After several hours of diverting sewage before the broken line was exposed, the line was cleared, and repaired.

PW operator arrival date/time since it's prior to date City learned of sewage spill (Cal Am break occurred 08/23/17 when City responded) and it wasn't until 08/24/17 after clean-up that City rcvd video of sewer overflow due to Cal Am water break. Cal Am 16-inch water main break occurred at approx. 8 p.m. (20:00 hrs) on 08/23/2017; first responders Cal Am, City Fire and Public Works did not identify sewer overflow at time of emergency. Sewer overflow occurred downstream of water main break. Potable water flowed into City sanitary sewer collection system, surcharging a manhole. On 08/24/2017 at approx. 4 p.m. (1600 hrs), City received social media video showing sewage flowing from downstream sewer manhole approx. 8:20 p.m. prior night 08/23/2017. City Public Works arrived on scene 08/23/2017 approx. 9:00 p.m. (2100 hrs) and did not observe sewage flow in area. Hence, City estimates a 1-hour sewage flow at 1.5-gallon per second for 60 minutes (City Engineer/PW Director estimated flow rate based on social media video). City staff in area all day 08/24/2017 conducting investigations and inspection of event area and City infrastructure.

The direct cause of the spill was an accumulation of debris, mainly toilet tissue, that caused a block in the sewer main. The underlying cause, however, was a separation of the sewer pipe at a connecting point between two lengths of pipe where the bottom of the pipe separated approximately 1-2 inches. This created a small differential in height between the underbed of the pipe and the pipe lip. Toilet tissue and debris got hung up on the lip and additional toilet tissue and debris started to get caught up on the prior tissue until it accumulated to the point that it obstructed flow in the pipe. Where the offset occurred, an additional lateral was tied into the main. After exposing the pipe in order to repair the offset, the contractor performing the repair stated that it appeared that when the wye for the additional lateral was installed, that there was insufficient compaction under the lateral. This allowed the lateral to settle which applied pressure the main eventually  stretching  and deforming to rubber couplers. This pressure and deformation are what finally caused the offset in the main.
